# AeroCap — Architecture Rules
# Lives at: .claude/architecture.rules — this repo only
# Purpose : Naming conventions, structural expectations, repo organisation rules
# Loaded  : Referenced by CLAUDE.md; apply to all code generation in this repo

## Naming Conventions

| Artifact | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Files | kebab-case | `booking-service.ts` |
| Classes / Types / Interfaces | PascalCase | `ReservationService` |
| Functions / variables | camelCase | `createReservation()` |
| DB tables | snake_case | `pilot_profiles` |
| DB columns | snake_case | `tenant_id`, `deleted_at` |
| EventBridge events | `Domain.Entity.PastTense` | `Booking.Reservation.Created` |
| AWS resources | `aerocap-{env}-{service}-{resource}` | `aerocap-prod-booking-table` |
| AWS environments | `dev` / `staging` / `prod` | |
| Tenant schemas | `tenant_{tenantId}` | `tenant_air-france-01` |
| API routes | `/api/v{N}/{domain}/{resource}` | `/api/v1/booking/reservations` |

## Repository Structure

```
AeroCap/
├── CLAUDE.md                  # Project memory (this file's parent)
├── .claude/
│   ├── architecture.rules     # ← You are here
│   ├── settings.json          # Hooks wiring
│   └── commands/              # Slash commands (skills invocation)
├── skills/                    # L2 Knowledge layer
├── hooks/                     # L3 Guardrail scripts
├── subagents/                 # L4 Delegation agents
├── plugins/                   # L5 Distribution
├── compliance/                # Living compliance documents
├── apps/
│   └── web/                   # Next.js frontend (App Router)
└── services/
    ├── user-service/
    ├── booking-service/
    ├── cbta-service/
    ├── hris-service/
    └── reporting-service/
```

## Microservice Internal Structure (enforced)

```
services/{name}-service/
├── src/
│   ├── handlers/       # Route handlers — input validation + response only
│   ├── services/       # Business logic — no DB, no HTTP
│   ├── repositories/   # DB queries — all queries include tenant_id
│   ├── events/         # EventBridge publish + consume
│   ├── schemas/        # Zod schemas — single source of truth for types
│   ├── types/          # TypeScript interfaces (extend Zod inferred types)
│   └── index.ts        # Express app bootstrap
├── tests/
│   └── integration/    # testcontainers — real DB, no mocks
├── migrations/         # Sequential SQL files: 001_init.sql, 002_...sql
├── openapi.yaml        # Written BEFORE implementation, not after
└── package.json
```

## Multi-Tenancy Rules (CRITICAL)

```
✅ SELECT * FROM tenant_{tenantId}.reservations WHERE tenant_id = $1
❌ SELECT * FROM reservations  (missing tenant schema + filter)
❌ SELECT * FROM reservations WHERE tenant_id = req.body.tenantId  (user-controlled)

✅ const tenantId = req.user.tenantId  (from verified JWT)
❌ const tenantId = req.body.tenantId  (user-controlled — NEVER)
❌ const tenantId = req.params.tenantId (user-controlled — NEVER)
```

## API Contract Rules

- OpenAPI 3.0 spec: write it first, implement second — no exceptions.
- Response envelope: `{ data: T | null, meta: { requestId, timestamp, page?, limit?, total? }, error: null | { code, message } }`
- All IDs: UUID format (`format: uuid`). Never sequential integers in API.
- Pagination: every list endpoint has `page`, `limit`, `total`.
- Auth: `bearerAuth` on every endpoint except `/health` and `/api/auth/...`.
- Errors: always structured — never plain strings, never stack traces to client.

## TypeScript Rules

- `"strict": true` — always on, no exceptions.
- No `any`. Use `unknown` + type narrowing, or Zod `safeParse`.
- No `// @ts-ignore`. Fix the type, don't suppress it.
- Props interfaces: exported, named `{Component}Props`.
- Zod schemas are the single source of type truth — export inferred types, don't duplicate.
- Barrel exports: every module folder has an `index.ts`.
- Co-locate tests: `feature.ts` and `feature.test.ts` in the same directory.

## Event Design Rules

Every EventBridge event payload MUST include:
```typescript
{
  tenantId: string;    // mandatory
  eventId: string;     // UUID — for idempotency
  timestamp: string;   // ISO 8601
  version: number;     // integer — for schema evolution
  // ... domain fields
}
```
Consumers are idempotent. Duplicate delivery must be handled safely.
Never use events for synchronous request/response.

## Testing Rules

- Unit tests: Jest. 80% minimum coverage on service layer.
- Integration tests: testcontainers (real PostgreSQL). No DB mocks.
- E2E tests: Playwright. Cover all critical user flows (login, booking, CBTA report).
- Test naming: `it('should {expected} when {condition}', ...)`.
- Every repository method has a tenant isolation test — a mandatory, non-negotiable test case.

## Security Rules

- Secrets: AWS Secrets Manager only. Never `.env` files, never source code.
- JWT: validate signature + expiry + issuer (`iss`) + audience (`aud`) on every request.
- Input: Zod parse at handler boundary before any business logic.
- SQL: parameterized queries only. No string interpolation in SQL.
- Logs: never log JWT tokens, passwords, or PII fields.
- CORS: never `*` in production. Whitelist only.

## Git / PR Rules

- Branch naming: `{type}/{ticket}-{description}` e.g. `feat/AC-42-booking-calendar`
- Commit format: `{type}(scope): message` e.g. `feat(booking): add waiting list support`
- Every PR must pass: lint + unit tests + tenant isolation review (`/review-tenant-isolation`)
- No force push to `main`. No `--no-verify`. No skipping hooks.
- PRs touching PII or compliance: require compliance-auditor subagent run before merge.
